## Thread.Abort â†’ Cooperative Cancellation Migration

Your code has three patterns that break on .NET 8:

| API | .NET 8 behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never fires (no abort = no exception) |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### Classification

| Location | Pattern | Replacement |
|----------|---------|-------------|
| `Stop()` â†’ `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `ProcessLoop()` â†’ `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control-flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `ProcessLoop()` â†’ `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `GetNextItem()` blocking | Blocking call interruption | Pass `CancellationToken` to unblock |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work â€” mirrors the old ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed. We control whether to continue or exit
                // via the while loop condition. Loop will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts == null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        if (_workerThread != null && _workerThread.IsAlive)
        {
            bool exited = _workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
            if (!exited)
            {
                // Log a warning â€” the thread is stuck in uncooperative code.
                // There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort in modern .NET.
                // If this happens, GetNextItem must be fixed to honor the token.
            }
        }

        _cts.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### Critical: You must update `GetNextItem`

The old code relied on `Thread.Abort` to forcibly interrupt `GetNextItem` when it blocked. In .NET 8, **nothing will interrupt it unless it checks the token**. This is the most common migration pitfall.

```csharp
// BEFORE â€” blocks indefinitely, relied on Thread.Abort to escape
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks forever if queue is empty
}

// AFTER â€” unblocks when cancellation is requested
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
}

// If using a plain queue without CancellationToken support:
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!_queue.TryDequeue(out var item))
    {
        token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(100); // poll with cancellation
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    }
    return item;
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Not passing token to `GetNextItem`** | The thread hangs forever in `Stop()` â€” no abort exists to rescue it |
| **`Thread.Sleep` in blocking code** | `Thread.Sleep` ignores the token. Use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` instead |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers and callbacks. Always `Dispose()` after the thread exits |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException` broadly** | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not unrelated ones |
| **Expecting cancellation to be instant** | It's cooperative â€” only fires at the next checkpoint. If `ProcessItem` runs for minutes without checking, cancellation waits |

### `Thread.Sleep` in `Stop()` â†’ `Thread.Join`

The original `Thread.Sleep(2000)` was a blind wait. `Thread.Join(TimeSpan)` is strictly better â€” it returns early if the thread exits before the timeout and tells you whether it succeeded.

### Summary of API mappings

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|----------------|--------|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Remove â€” loop condition handles continuation |
| `Thread.Sleep(ms)` | `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` |
| `_queue.Take()` | `_queue.Take(token)` |
